davek725 wrote:
&gt; My company is currently doing TDD and using JUnit for our unit 
&gt; testing - both persistence testing and business logic testing.  We 
&gt; are now looking at Agitator and trying to determine if, and how, it 
&gt; fits into our current practices.  I was wondering how others have 
&gt; decided to use Agitator (or not use it).  Some of the issues we are 
&gt; struggling with:
&gt; 
&gt; 1.  Agitator looks like it can eliminate the need to write most JUnit 
&gt; tests (except true persistence testing).  The downside is that we 
&gt; would be left with only Agitator config files that contain our 
&gt; business logic assertions.  This seems like a big leap to take, given 
&gt; that if Agitar goes away, we have no JUnit.
&gt; 
&gt; 2.  Agitator mocks and factories look easy to create, but look like 
&gt; they are only useful in the context of Agitator.  I couldn&#39;t use them 
&gt; for other purposes (e.g. Fitnesse, JUnit).
&gt; 
&gt; 3.  Having my business logic tests in JUnit means they are in an 
&gt; understood format and things such as inputs and expected results are 
&gt; clearly visible and grouped with each test.  My impression of 
&gt; Agitator is that this wouldn&#39;t be as clear.
